T1  - Do serial entrepreneurs run successively better-performing businesses?
AU  - Parker, Simon C.
JO  - Journal of Business Venturing
VL  - 28
IS  - 5
SP  - 652
EP  - 666
PY  - 2013
DA  - 2013/09/01/
SN  - 0883-9026
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jbusvent.2012.08.001
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0883902612000894
KW  - Serial entrepreneurship
KW  - Performance
KW  - Self-employment
AB  - This paper investigates whether – consistent with theories of entrepreneurial learning by doing and resource acquisition – serial entrepreneurs' performance follows a rising trajectory over successive venturing spells. Or whether – consistent with theories of selective learning from failure and hubris – serial entrepreneurs perform better after experiencing a bad spell (and worse after experiencing a good spell). We test competing hypotheses about serial entrepreneurs' performance trajectories using Panel Study of Income Dynamics (PSID) data, which track the dynamic performance of a sample of American serial entrepreneurs for up to one-quarter of a century. The findings show that serial entrepreneurs obtain temporary benefits from spells of venturing which eventually die away. This implies that venturing generates benefits which spill over from one venture into subsequent ones, and it can provide a rationale for public policies which encourage re-entries by entrepreneurs, even if those entrepreneurs performed poorly in their first ventures.
